Question 1

Question:
Create two user-defined packages pkg1 and pkg2 and import both into another program which is outside the packages.

Program

pkg1/First.java

package pkg1;

public class First {
    public void show() {
        System.out.println("This is pkg1 class");
    }
}


pkg2/Second.java

package pkg2;

public class Second {
    public void display() {
        System.out.println("This is pkg2 class");
    }
}


Main.java

import pkg1.First;
import pkg2.Second;

class Main {
    public static void main(String args[]) {
        First f = new First();
        Second s = new Second();

        f.show();
        s.display();
    }
}

Output
This is pkg1 class
This is pkg2 class

Explanation:

Two user-defined packages are created and imported into another program using the import keyword.

Question 2

Question:
Create multiple packages containing classes with identical names.

Program

pkg1/Test.java

package pkg1;

public class Test {
    public void show() {
        System.out.println("Test class from pkg1");
    }
}


pkg2/Test.java

package pkg2;

public class Test {
    public void show() {
        System.out.println("Test class from pkg2");
    }
}


Main.java

class Main {
    public static void main(String args[]) {
        pkg1.Test t1 = new pkg1.Test();
        pkg2.Test t2 = new pkg2.Test();

        t1.show();
        t2.show();
    }
}

Output
Test class from pkg1
Test class from pkg2

Explanation:

Same class names can exist in different packages and are accessed using package name + class name.

Question 3

Question:
Show how a protected variable of one package can be accessed in a subclass of another package.

Program

pkg1/Base.java

package pkg1;

public class Base {
    protected int x = 10;
}


pkg2/Derived.java

package pkg2;
import pkg1.Base;

public class Derived extends Base {
    public static void main(String args[]) {
        Derived d = new Derived();
        System.out.println("Protected variable x = " + d.x);
    }
}

Output
Protected variable x = 10

Explanation:

A protected variable can be accessed in another package only through inheritance.

Question 4

Question:
Show how to add multiple public classes to a single package.

Program

mypkg/ClassA.java

package mypkg;

public class ClassA {
    public void showA() {
        System.out.println("This is Class A");
    }
}


mypkg/ClassB.java

package mypkg;

public class ClassB {
    public void showB() {
        System.out.println("This is Class B");
    }
}


Main.java

import mypkg.ClassA;
import mypkg.ClassB;

class Main {
    public static void main(String args[]) {
        ClassA a = new ClassA();
        ClassB b = new ClassB();

        a.showA();
        b.showB();
    }
}

Output
This is Class A
This is Class B

Explanation:

A single package can contain multiple public classes, each saved in a separate file.
